We are officially a family of three. Sebastian Garnsworthy Street arrived earlier this week and I can confirm that every cliche thing everyone says about having a baby is true. He’s just the best. ❤️

Our first week with Sebastian has been pure joy and I credit this beautiful start to all of the support we’ve had. 

First of all the medical team and facilities at Alexandra Cohen Hospital were phenomenal. I was induced, had a 26 hour labor, and he arrived 10 days late in the end, so we spent a total of four nights in the hospital and felt completely cared for and supported the entire time. Steve and I went into this having never changed a nappy, and I’ve barely even held a newborn. The learning curve has been steep and we’ve had our hands held at every step—it’s been a great start.

Then we transferred to @boramcare, a space entirely dedicated to postpartum care that has made this transition much easier—particularly the 24/7 lactation consultants, newborn care classes and healthy food. I’ll share more on this soon (most of the experience has been kindly gifted) but for now I just wanted to say hello from our happy little love bubble, and share both of these recommendations.

(Swipe to pic 5 to see what my frown lines look like without Botox 🫠)

THIS is the ‘glass cliff” theory IRL. (Part 1 of 2)

I posted this to TikTok and LinkedIn over the weekend, and people are curious. So let’s dive in. 

The theory says when a company is in really bad shape, women step in to clean up the mess.

Usually, they’re set up to lose, and are pushed off a ‘glass cliff’ and take the fall for the company’s failure.

This is exactly what we’re seeing unfold at Twitter right now.

It might be that women are trusted to clean up the mess. 

More likely though, it’s that men feel confident turning down a leadership role offered under tough conditions knowing that another opportunity will come up, while women feel like it’s their only shot so say yes—even if they’re being set up to fail.

Follow for part 2.

Spaghetti Sundays is a tradition Steve and I started years ago as expats in New York that now travels wherever we go. It’s a family meal for your chosen family, hosted every Sunday. The rule is: if you’ve been invited once you’re invited forever, just byo wine and drop around in the afternoon. 

Now our family and friends host their own Spaghetti Sundays in their cities and send us photos of their people around a table with a big bowl of pasta. It’s lovely. 

Just a reminder that you get to make your own traditions in this life. And if you can’t think of something, feel free to steal this one and do your own Spaghetti Sundays. ❤️

It could be easy to feel a little petty and jealous of @adrianacarrig. 

Last year her business—which she had, until this point, built without any help from investors—made $20 million. From selling $25 bracelets! It’s a lot of bracelets. She also has a beautiful family, which she built alongside the company.

She’s also exactly my age, which is always a fun comparison.

Except, honestly, she’s too nice. Which is kind of the point. 

Her business @littlewordsproject started ten years ago to spread kindness. 

They make beaded word bracelets with positive affirmations. The idea is that when you don’t need yours anymore, you can pass it on to someone who does. Each bracelet can be registered online, so you can follow it as it travels spreading good through the world. 

It’s genuinely a lovely initiative, but also a genius word of mouth marketing tactic. 

Adriana and her team have had lots of smart ideas like that, which helped turn a $5k initial investment to buy some beads and business registration fees when Adriana was in college into a company that is on track to make $35 million this year. 

The mission also helped Adriana rally a dedicated community around the brand. They’re so strong, icons like Barbie and Dunkin’ have collaborated with Little Words Project, just to tap in.

She’s on the @femalefounderworld podcast this week, I hope you like it.

I put a lot of pressure on myself to achieve work goals before having babies, and I imagined that I'd become professionally irrelevant once I became a mum. 

I know this to be nonsense now, but I didn't see many examples of women building businesses while also building a family when I was coming up in my career, and the business piece is what I wanted more.

Then, I had Sebastian and entered my *matriarch era* and while every other priority in my life fell down a rung, it wasn’t that work became an afterthought, it’s that now career success has been contextualised through the lens of what it means for him, his life, and the time we will have together. And wow, if there was a fire within me before, now there’s a new purpose behind the hours and the effort I put in. 

I’ll move mountains for you baby boy. 

Thank you to @theinarra for interviewing me about all this, capturing the most delicious photos of Sebastian, and forcing me to reflect on the most monumental nine months of my life time. 

And one thing no one told me about having a baby: there’s an entire secret army of working and self-employed mums all across the world. Having a baby doesn’t shrink your professional world, it cracks open a whole new level of connection and community and comraderie with thousands of women.

I took zero days maternity leave. 

I was on Slack and email right after Seb was born, and hosted a 400+ person party for small biz owners five-and-a-half weeks later.

Don’t 🤮. It’s not what you think.

I’ve been showing this transition on Stories and you guys have questions so let’s clear some things up. I didn’t do this because I’m some masochist or Virgo-rising superwoman, but because I have two things:

1. A husband with excellent parental leave who did everything except breastfeed our baby.

2. The immense privilege and good luck and equally sticky challenge to be self employed in a business just big enough to have a small team that required direction, but not big enough that I could afford to replace myself for mat leave without risking the entire business.

So I started motherhood the way I intended to go on indefinitely: working a few hours every day and a little at night, seven days a week, and caring for my baby the rest. 

It was the only option, yes. But I’m certain this blend is why I’ve loved this new life stage—I didn’t feel like I lost any part of myself because I didn’t completely give up that big identity-shaper, work, for any period of time. I also love my work and small team (hi Paige! Hi Nat!).

It’s been an exhausting year, but worth it. If you are lucky enough to be a woman who is self employed and who has agency over her schedule and bank account, don’t let that go.

Now @femalefounderworld is heading into 2024 with a clear direction and path to grow, and I have a better understanding of my limits and when I’m pushing things too far. 

My approach isn’t for everyone and if I have a second baby I hope I can relax into the newborn time a little more deeply. But all this to say: if you’re self employed and thinking about starting a family, it can be done. It’s going to take everything you’ve got, but if you think creatively about what life can look like and you have some support, it can be extremely rewarding.

I’d love to know what your parental leave situation looked like, mums and dads. Particularly if you’re self employed or building a business 👇

Female Founder World Summit tickets just dropped! 

As we got closer to the end of 2023 we started thinking, “OK, so who’s throwing the end-of-year party for small biz owners, solopreneurs, and founders?” No one, apparently. So we scratched the rest of Female Founder World’s Q4 plans to host the best, biggest, most inspiring, helpful, fun day for our Business Besties in Brooklyn. And here we are. 

Meet: Female Founder World Summit, the ultimate end-of-year party for people who don’t usually get an end-of-year party. 

This is part conference, part party. You’ll hear talks from Allison Ellsworth (Poppi), Julie Rice (SoulCycle and Peoplehood), Rooshy Roy (AAVRANI), Adriana Carrig (Little Words Project), Daniela Pierson (The Newsette), and more wildly inspiring speakers I’m going to run out of space in this IG caption if I list them all.

We’ll have @mayssa as DJ. There will be a @nomadica wine bar, a relaxation station by @wthn, brand popups, packed gift bags and ✨vibes✨.

Lucky 33 🎲! @babba hosted us at her new Tuxedo Park home last night for the most glam casino-meets-Gatsby birthday party.

Fun story for you. Prince Edward VII started wearing the tuxedo as a less formal alternative to the tailcoat. This was back in the 1860s.

Then an American billionaire met the Prince on a trip to Britain, got himself a suit, and wore it to a private country club in Tuxedo Park, New York. 

You see, a wealthy, Aristocratic New York community had been formed around Tuxedo Park and the country club there. 

It had developed into an elite group of wealthy men that formed what was eventually known as the Tuxedo Club. These guys made the tuxedo their thing and it spread across America and really hit its stride during the 1920s Gatsby era.

Anyway, don’t tell me influencer marketing doesn’t work!
